Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

First-time manager transition coaching
High Output Management principles (Andy Grove)
Radical Candor framework (Kim Scott) — care personally, challenge directly
1-on-1 meeting structure and effectiveness
Delegation as a multiplier (not abdication)
Performance management and difficult conversations
Hiring and team composition strategy
Strategic thinking and prioritization (OKRs at team level)
Managing up and cross-functional influence
Building psychological safety in teams

Methodologies & Frameworks
Management: High Output Management (Grove), The Manager's Path (Fournier), First Break All the Rules (Gallup)
Feedback: Radical Candor (Scott), SBI model (Situation, Behavior, Impact), Feedforward (Goldsmith)
Meetings: 1-on-1 template, Team standup, Skip-level meetings, Retrospectives
Delegation: RACI matrix, Skill-Will matrix, Delegation levels (tell, sell, consult, delegate, empower)
Decision Making: DACI framework, Disagree and commit, Reversible vs. irreversible decisions
Team Health: Psychological safety assessment, Lencioni's 5 Dysfunctions, Team topology

Reference Documentation
1. First-Time Manager Playbook
Comprehensive guide covering:
- The identity shift: "What got you here won't get you there"
- Your output = your team's output, not your individual contribution
- First 90 days: Listen tour, quick wins, relationship building
- Common trap: Doing the work yourself instead of enabling others
- Building trust through consistency, vulnerability, and follow-through

2. Feedback Frameworks
Complete feedback library:
- Radical Candor quadrant: Ruinous Empathy, Manipulative Insincerity, Obnoxious Aggression, Radical Candor
- SBI: "In [Situation], when you [Behavior], the impact was [Impact]..."
- Praise ratios: 3-5 positive interactions per 1 corrective (Losada ratio)
- Real-time feedback > annual review — shorten the loop
- Ask: "Can I give you some feedback?" — establishes consent and frames the conversation

3. Delegation Mastery
Technical reference with:
- The Skill-Will matrix for delegation decisions
- Level 1: "Do exactly this" → Level 5: "Own this completely, inform me of results"
- Common mistake: Delegating the task but not the authority
- Over-delegation = abandonment, Under-delegation = micromanagement
- Delegation unlocks YOUR time for strategic work — it's not optional

Leadership Patterns
Pattern 1: Effective 1-on-1 Structure
Weekly 30-minute manager-report meetings:
- First 10 min: Employee's agenda (their concerns, updates, blockers)
- Next 10 min: Manager's agenda (feedback, alignment, priorities)
- Last 10 min: Career development and growth conversations
- Never cancel 1-on-1s — rescheduling is okay, canceling sends a message
- Take shared notes and track action items

Pattern 2: Difficult Conversation Framework
Addressing underperformance or conflict:
- Prepare: Write down specific behaviors (not character), impact, and desired change
- Open: "I want to discuss something I've observed. Is now a good time?"
- Deliver: SBI model — Situation, Behavior, Impact (specific, not vague)
- Listen: Their perspective may reveal context you're missing
- Agree on next steps: Specific, time-bound, documented
- Follow up: Check in on progress, don't set-and-forget

Pattern 3: Strategic Prioritization
Ensuring team works on what matters most:
- Define 3 (not 10) team OKRs per quarter
- Run every new request through: "Does this serve our OKRs?"
- Protect the team from distraction — "No" is a leadership skill
- Communicate the WHY behind priorities, not just the WHAT
- Review progress weekly, adjust monthly, reset quarterly

Best Practices
Leadership
- Your team's success IS your success — stop doing, start enabling
- Trust is built in drops and lost in buckets — be consistent
- Psychological safety is the #1 predictor of high-performing teams (Project Aristotle)
- Give credit publicly, give feedback privately — always
- The best leaders are the best listeners — listen 2x more than you speak

Management
- Regular 1-on-1s are your most important management activity
- Make decisions at the lowest competent level — don't be the bottleneck
- Document expectations clearly — assumed standards aren't standards
- When in doubt, over-communicate — especially during change
- Hiring is the highest leverage activity — never rush it

Growth
- Read widely outside your domain — cross-pollination creates innovation
- Find a peer group of other leaders — the role can be lonely
- Ask your team for feedback on YOUR leadership — and act on it
- Mentor someone — teaching clarifies your own thinking
- Your energy sets the team's energy — manage your own state first

